# ION — Cursor carrier onboarding, V94 canonical

## First truth

Cursor is only the host/carrier. ION is the workflow.

The parent Cursor chat is `CURSOR_CARRIER_CONTROL_SURFACE`, not STEWARD or any other ION role.

## Shell root

Confirm the root by requiring both files in the same directory:

```text
pyproject.toml
ION/REPO_AUTHORITY.md
```

No fixed path is canonical. If this root cannot be found, stop with `ROOT_NOT_CONFIRMED`.

## `/ion` is the onboarding/reset command

On `/ion`, `continue`, `proceed`, `resume`, or any substantive operator message about ION work, run the canonical V94 sequence from shell root.

If no message follows `/ion`, use `continue`.

```bash
PYTHONDONTWRITEBYTECODE=1 PYTHONPATH=ION/04_packages python3 -S -m kernel.ion_cursor_autopilot_packet --ion-root . --operator-message "<message-or-continue>" --write --json
PYTHONDONTWRITEBYTECODE=1 PYTHONPATH=ION/04_packages python3 -S -m kernel.ion_carrier_continue --ion-root . --carrier cursor --operator-message "<message-or-continue>" --consume-operator-queue --json
```

Then read:

```text
ION/05_context/current/ACTIVE_CURSOR_AUTOPILOT_PACKET.json
ION/05_context/current/ACTIVE_CARRIER_TURN_PACKET.json
ION/05_context/current/ACTIVE_ROLE_SPAWN_PLAN.json
```

## Deprecated older route

Do not use `python3 -m kernel <workstream> "<objective>"` as the parent-chat proof of onboarding. It is an internal/backward-compatible workstream call only when a generated packet explicitly instructs it.

Do not manually combine `ion_carrier_onboard` and `ion_cycle_runner` unless `ion_carrier_continue` is unavailable and the degraded fallback is recorded.

## Subagents

Launch Cursor subagents only from generated spawn rows. Give the generated `context_package_path` content. Require `### CONTEXT PROOF`. Capture and intake returns through `kernel.ion_carrier_task_return`.

## Operator burden

Never ask the user to manage ION upkeep, choose routine agents, refresh packets, update context, or sequence normal work. Ask only for explicit human gates, direction changes, external permission, destructive/action scope, or true root ambiguity.
